Patch Set 2:

Using this oslo.messaging functionality might be a simpler way to achieve this:
    https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/oslo.messaging/+/546763

Patch Set 2:

> Using this oslo.messaging functionality might be a simpler way to achieve this:
>     https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/oslo.messaging/+/546763

Yeah, so with that, you can leave things as calls that you want to be calls. They will be allowed to run longer than the usual timeout (up to the long-call timeout upper bound). o.msg will automatically heartbeat back to the caller at half the usual timeout interval to let it know it should keep waiting. Because of this, the same RPC timeout semantics are held for the case where the remote side just quietly dies so that we notice and return a timely error to the caller (user, if via the API). No new versions required (assuming your o.msg isn't super ancient on both sides), and the manager side doesn't need to even know about this.

In nova, we default to allow these long calls to run up to 30 minutes if they're really running (i.e. heartbeating) and that allows us to keep our actual timeout at 60s for non-responsive things.

Example here:

 https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/rpcapi.py#L596

Because of this, the same RPC timeout semantics are held for the case where the remote side just quietly dies so that we notice and return a timely error to the caller (user, if via the API). No new versions required (assuming your o.msg isn't super ancient on both sides), and the manager side doesn't need to even know about this.
> 
> In nova, we default to allow these long calls to run up to 30 minutes if they're really running (i.e. heartbeating) and that allows us to keep our actual timeout at 60s for non-responsive things.
> 
> Example here:
> 
>  https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/rpcapi.py#L596

I think this is the wrong approach here as 2Tb volume copies (clones) can take hours to complete.  It's much more reliable to have a callback in this case.   Keeping around rpc calls for hours seems just ripe for errors and issues to come up.

Patch Set 2:

> I think this is the wrong approach here as 2Tb volume copies (clones) can take hours to complete.  It's much more reliable to have a callback in this case.   Keeping around rpc calls for hours seems just ripe for errors and issues to come up.

Surely, if you're talking about hours, and/or something that scales with user-controllable size, then definitely better not to hold the RPC reply queue the whole time. Since this is currently a call and the normal timeout is very very short, I figured the goal was to have it retain call-like semantics but just be tolerant of it taking more than a minute.

Patch Set 2:

Thanks, that makes sense.  I agree that the new approach here would be better than holding the rpc calls open for hours.

Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

(7 comments)

I could write up some tests for this POC and we could carry it until s3api is using ALOs

... or we could try to tease out some of the s3api specific bits from the proxy and object server such that it's doing something generic with sysmeta and then call it a real improvement to the expirer to handle s3api DELETE responses.  Maybe even s3api itself could benifit (no more HEAD before every DELETE?), or somehow even PUT overwrite responses could take advantage of similar "best effort" cleanup.

Patch Set 3:

> Do you know why this issue wasn't caught by the tests (any tests:
 > unit, temmpest)? Do you have any suggestion on a test that could
 > prevent regressions?

I find that all the unit tests have additional fixture or properties in the image, then image has 'is_public' attribute. Examples of unit tests are as follows：
    def test_show_raises_when_no_authtoken_in_the_context(self):
        fixture = self._make_fixture(name='image1',
                                     is_public=False,
                                     protected=False)
        image_id = self.service.create(self.context, fixture)['id']

or,
    def test_show_shared_image_membership_fail_status(self):
    ...
        image = {
            'id': image_id,
            'name': 'test image',
            ...
            'properties': {'is_public': False},
            'visibility': None,
        }

If image has no additional properties，it may cause code bug when context no authtoken. I think this needs to be fixed.
